Closet cabinets are floor-to-ceiling units with doors, and have the appearance of built-in furniture. They may be used as linen closets, or to conceal washer/dryer units or water heaters. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Base cabinets are freestanding cabinets that sit on the floor. These cabinets come in a wide variety of shapes and sizes, and can be placed anywhere in the bathroom. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f5/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f5/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Wall cabinets are hung on the wall, usually over a bathroom fixture. For example, medicine cabinets are narrow units that are generally placed within reach from the sink area, while open-shelved cabinets may be installed over the toilet area for toilet tissue storage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A bathroom cabinet should fit into its environment, so you will want to choose cabinetry that complements your home's existing furniture and architectural details. Consider the following design elements:
Doors. You may opt for open-shelved cabinets, which have no doors, or for decorative glass or solid doors. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Material. Bathroom cabinets come in a wide array of materials, including wood, plastic, wicker, glass, bamboo, porcelain and laminate. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Accessories. Pay attention to things like drawer pulls, door handles, cabinet tops and mirrors, as these details contribute to the cabinet's aesthetic and style. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/58/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/58/Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Select-a-Bathroom-Cabinet-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
